00:47:45.135 --> 00:47:45.827
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:47:45.827 --> 00:47:46.660
SOPHIE DELAUNAY: OK.

00:47:46.660 --> 00:47:51.640
So evacuation is a criteria
in a high security area.

00:47:51.640 --> 00:47:55.860
It's not a criteria
everywhere, of course, right?

00:47:55.860 --> 00:48:00.440
But the main criteria for
deciding to open a center

00:48:00.440 --> 00:48:04.890
is mortality, of course.

00:48:04.890 --> 00:48:08.030
So are we going to
have an added value?

00:48:08.030 --> 00:48:10.030
There can be high mortality,
but we know nothing

00:48:10.030 --> 00:48:11.300
about this disease, right?

00:48:11.300 --> 00:48:12.930
Or we can't do
anything about it.

00:48:12.930 --> 00:48:14.770
So its our own added value.

00:48:14.770 --> 00:48:17.880
And is there anybody
else who can do it?

00:48:17.880 --> 00:48:20.200
Is there is another
organization better

00:48:20.200 --> 00:48:23.410
placed to respond than us?

00:48:23.410 --> 00:48:26.660
So this would be the
first criteria to decide.

00:48:26.660 --> 00:48:29.670
So neglect is very
important, as you see,

00:48:29.670 --> 00:48:31.590
because it's both
can we do something

00:48:31.590 --> 00:48:33.040
about it that others can't do?

00:48:33.040 --> 00:48:36.658
And is it really killing people?

00:48:36.658 --> 00:48:39.714
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:39.714 --> 00:48:40.630
SOPHIE DELAUNAY: Yeah.

00:48:40.630 --> 00:48:42.410
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:42.410 --> 00:48:47.060
You mentioned the concept
of operational neutrality

00:48:47.060 --> 00:48:51.540
and keeping your donations
from governments to 15%

00:48:51.540 --> 00:48:54.080
to sort of safeguard that.

00:48:54.080 --> 00:48:57.134
What about investment
neutrality?

00:48:57.134 --> 00:48:58.550
And what I mean
by that is, well I

00:48:58.550 --> 00:49:00.216
guess there's really
two questions here.

00:49:00.216 --> 00:49:03.380
So number one is, is
there government money

00:49:03.380 --> 00:49:06.940
that you're saying
no to to guarantee

00:49:06.940 --> 00:49:08.720
your operational neutrality?

00:49:08.720 --> 00:49:12.540
And number two is, the concept
of investment neutrality

00:49:12.540 --> 00:49:15.100
would be you mentioned the
fact that there a lot of things

00:49:15.100 --> 00:49:18.340
you'd like investment in, but
the problem is those things

00:49:18.340 --> 00:49:21.250
don't happen in maybe,
like the West, right?

00:49:21.250 --> 00:49:23.410
So there isn't an
investment in those things,

00:49:23.410 --> 00:49:24.840
because people don't see it.

00:49:24.840 --> 00:49:28.780
So is there a way to
maybe-- you're not

00:49:28.780 --> 00:49:30.880
taking operational
monies, but you're

00:49:30.880 --> 00:49:33.650
taking investment money that can
be redirected to those causes?

00:49:38.580 --> 00:49:40.010
SOPHIE DELAUNAY: Yes.

00:49:40.010 --> 00:49:42.900
There are definitely
investments that we

00:49:42.900 --> 00:49:44.820
wouldn't take from government.

00:49:44.820 --> 00:49:49.282
It's not just about taking
funding from government or not.

00:49:49.282 --> 00:49:54.150
It's about-- we may, for
example, receive funding

00:49:54.150 --> 00:50:02.080
from the field for some
research, for medical research.

00:50:02.080 --> 00:50:04.660
But we may not
want the funding--

00:50:04.660 --> 00:50:07.430
we would not want the funding
from defeat for Afghanistan,

00:50:07.430 --> 00:50:08.110
for example.

00:50:08.110 --> 00:50:08.610
Right?

00:50:08.610 --> 00:50:11.990
So depending on the
nature of the funding,

00:50:11.990 --> 00:50:14.245
we will make some arbitration.

00:50:19.310 --> 00:50:21.530
If I understood your
question, is there

00:50:21.530 --> 00:50:24.710
a way not to get the money, but
to ensure that this money is

00:50:24.710 --> 00:50:28.980
invested so that it
serves our purpose, right?

00:50:28.980 --> 00:50:31.760
Well, this is what we try
to do through advocacy.

00:50:31.760 --> 00:50:33.300
And this is why I
said we don't want

00:50:33.300 --> 00:50:36.940
to be constantly
filling the gaps.

00:50:36.940 --> 00:50:39.850
If there is no drug for
TB, it's not for MSF

00:50:39.850 --> 00:50:42.285
to develop a drug for TB, right?

00:50:47.040 --> 00:50:52.040
We have at dedicated some
resources to our advocacy

00:50:52.040 --> 00:50:57.350
so that we can try to influence
and mobilize the stakeholders--

00:50:57.350 --> 00:51:00.770
so, big pharma, the large
organizations like Garvey,

00:51:00.770 --> 00:51:02.350
like the Gates Foundations.

00:51:02.350 --> 00:51:04.410
And we have actually
people who are working

00:51:04.410 --> 00:51:06.980
on trying to influence their
agenda, and making sure

00:51:06.980 --> 00:51:10.910
that they are paying
attention to those aspects.

00:51:10.910 --> 00:51:15.010
We also where I think we
are the most successful

00:51:15.010 --> 00:51:19.810
is trying to demonstrate
that the protocol work.

00:51:19.810 --> 00:51:22.360
And then having WHO-- the
World Health Organization--

00:51:22.360 --> 00:51:26.220
adopt this as
normative protocol,

00:51:26.220 --> 00:51:28.280
because then it's the
best way for the countries

00:51:28.280 --> 00:51:33.076
to demand that those
protocols be applied.

00:51:33.076 --> 00:51:34.450
And when you have
a protocol, you

00:51:34.450 --> 00:51:38.290
need to have medicines that
also is adapted to them.

00:51:38.290 --> 00:51:41.640
We're also worked at
providing some specification.

00:51:41.640 --> 00:51:46.625
For example, we're working
with a number of lab

00:51:46.625 --> 00:51:49.650
who are working at
point-of-care test.

00:51:49.650 --> 00:51:53.620
And we provide them
with the wish list

00:51:53.620 --> 00:51:56.110
of what would be an
ideal point-of-care test

00:51:56.110 --> 00:51:58.962
in the countries where we work.

00:51:58.962 --> 00:51:59.670
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

